He earned his Bachelor?s and Master?s degrees at Kansas State Teachers College (now Emporia State University). He received an undergraduate fellowship to Argonne National Laboratory in Illinois. Larry was awarded his Ph.D. in botany in 1973 at the University of Kansas; his dissertation was entitled ?The Native Orchids of the Prairies and Plains Region of North America.? Orchids remained the primary focus of Larry?s research throughout his career.
